data.content:
Yes! MSTest 3.7+ supports **ValueTuple-based `DynamicData`**, eliminating the `object[]` boxing:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string input, bool expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**What changed:** The data property returns `IEnumerable<(string, bool)>` instead of `IEnumerable<object[]>`. This gives you:

- **Compile-time type safety** — wrong types won't compile
- **Named tuple elements** for readability
- **No boxing** of value types

If you also need per-case display names, wrap with `TestDataRow<T>`:

```csharp
public static IEnumerable<TestDataRow<(string input, bool expected)>> TestData =>
[
    new(("valid@email.com", true)) { DisplayName = "Valid email" },
    new(("invalid", false)) { DisplayName = "Missing domain" },
    new(("", false)) { DisplayName = "Empty string" },
];
```

Requires **MSTest 3.7+** (the `MSTest` package or `MSTest.Sdk`).
